    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4e7c9e6a-d72f-4346-8f8f-b21fc9b6badb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 34-year-old man in the Czech Republic who comes in looking uncomfortable but not toxic. He reports burning discomfort when urinating and urinary frequency, symptoms that are consistent with urinary tract infection [PMID:32913861]. He says the problem has made him tense at work because he keeps stepping away to use the bathroom and worries about the pain returning before the day is over. He is afebrile today by measurement, though he says he felt feverish at home earlier in the illness; fever can accompany urinary tract infection, especially when infection involves the upper tract [PMID:32913861].\n\nHe works as an IT support specialist and spends most of the day seated, drinks too much coffee, and often delays bathroom breaks during busy shifts. Outside work he plays five-a-side football on weekends and usually meets friends for beer once or twice a week. He lives with his partner and says the urinary burning has also made sex uncomfortable; painful intercourse and discomfort with urination were described in a patient discussion around UTI symptoms [MEDDIALOG:N39.0:2].\n\nOver the last 2 days he has noticed cloudy urine and mild suprapubic discomfort. He denies flank pain and appears relieved that he is still able to pass urine normally, unlike severe obstructive fungal urinary infections that can cause anuria in complicated cases [PMID:38148952]. He is worried because he has never had a UTI before and thought this was more common in women, but he came in because the dysuria and frequency were getting hard to ignore [PMID:32913861]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:c8c7f052-957d-4d9d-895b-98c921b8c50d",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no major chronic medical conditions and no prior hospitalizations. He reports 2 days of burning on urination and urinary frequency, with mild lower abdominal discomfort. He specifically denies flank pain, which is notable because flank pain and fever were described in upper tract or bacteremic urinary infection [PMID:32913861]. He has not had anuria or urinary retention; severe obstructive fungal UTI cases with anuria are described as rare complications [PMID:38148952].\n\n{patientName} is sexually active with one female partner and says urination has been uncomfortable, and sex has also felt uncomfortable during this episode, echoing symptoms reported in UTI-related patient dialogue [MEDDIALOG:N39.0:2]. He tries to stay active with recreational football but often drinks coffee, occasionally alcohol, and sometimes postpones voiding during work shifts. There is no history suggesting prior urinary procedures, kidney stones, or recurrent documented UTIs. He has no known medication intolerances except a remote rash with penicillin reported from childhood."
          }
        ]
      }
